{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17529489","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17529489"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:56:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:56:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14421"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14421","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14421"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.06,0.72,0.04,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7116"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100223"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7116","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7116"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14421"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82621"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"688"},{"type":"tags","id":"1307"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2747"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11691"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16976"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25052"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34437"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100223","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/100223"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of difficulty concentrating and memory problems. She reports making errors at work and forgetting important meetings. She feels tired but attributes this to poor sleep. She has gained 3 kg despite maintaining her usual diet. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She works as an accountant and is concerned about her job performance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well but has delayed responses to questions. Her pulse rate is 62/min, blood pressure 128/78 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. Mini-Mental State Examination score is 27/30 with deficits in recall and calculation. Neurological examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations is most likely to reveal an abnormality in this case?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Brain MRI with contrast","Serum cortisol","Thyroid-stimulating hormone","Vitamin B12 level","Neuropsychological testing"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a diagnostic challenge as the patient\u0027s symptoms primarily suggest a cognitive disorder, with subtle hints of hypothyroidism that could easily be overlooked. The cognitive symptoms, work performance issues, and relatively normal examination might lead clinicians toward neurological or primary psychiatric investigations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH)\u003C/strong\u003E remains the most appropriate investigation likely to reveal an abnormality. While the classical signs of hypothyroidism (cold intolerance, dry skin, obvious bradycardia) are not prominent, subtle clues include mild bradycardia, weight gain, and fatigue. TSH is highly sensitive for detecting early hypothyroidism, which can present with predominantly psychiatric or cognitive manifestations before developing more obvious physical signs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBrain MRI with contrast\u003C/strong\u003E might seem appropriate given the cognitive symptoms and professional impact, but is unlikely to reveal an abnormality. While it could detect structural causes of cognitive impairment, the gradual onset and absence of focal neurological signs make a space-occupying lesion or demyelination less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeuropsychological testing\u003C/strong\u003E would provide detailed information about cognitive deficits but would not identify the underlying cause. This would be more appropriate after excluding reversible medical causes of cognitive impairment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum cortisol\u003C/strong\u003E could be considered as both Cushing\u0027s syndrome and adrenal insufficiency can affect cognition, but the clinical picture lacks other suggestive features such as postural hypotension or cushingoid appearance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVitamin B12 level\u003C/strong\u003E testing is reasonable in investigating cognitive impairment, but the presence of other subtle features (bradycardia, weight gain) makes thyroid dysfunction a more likely underlying cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis case emphasizes the importance of considering hypothyroidism in patients presenting with cognitive or psychiatric symptoms, even when classical physical signs are minimal or absent. The threshold for thyroid function testing should be low, as it is an easily treatable cause of cognitive impairment that may present insidiously.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hypothyroidism can present primarily with psychiatric manifestations before developing classical physical signs.","TSH remains the most sensitive initial test for diagnosing primary hypothyroidism, even when psychiatric symptoms predominate.","Secondary causes of cognitive impairment must be excluded before attributing symptoms to primary psychiatric disorders."],"references":["So M, MacIsaac RJ, Grossmann M. Hypothyroidism: investigation and management. Australian Family Physician. 2012 Aug;41(8):556-62."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82621"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14421"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82621","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/82621"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-24T22:09:44+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-24T22:09:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7116"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100223"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"ite